---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="How to Get Assessed for AuDHD"
  description="A practical guide to getting assessed for AuDHD: types of professionals, what to expect, how to prepare, finding specialists, and what it costs."
  type="article"
>
  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 py-12">
    <header class="mb-10">
      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold text-text">How to Get Assessed for AuDHD</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-text-light leading-relaxed">
        You've read the articles. Taken the quizzes. Watched the TikToks. Everything points in the same direction, and now you want an actual assessment. But where do you go? Who do you ask? What even happens during an assessment? Here's what you need to know before you book anything.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="space-y-8">
      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Who Can Diagnose AuDHD?</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Not all mental health professionals can diagnose both autism and ADHD. A therapist or counselor can suspect it, but formal diagnosis typically requires a psychologist, psychiatrist, or neuropsychologist. The key distinction: you want someone who assesses <strong class="text-text">both conditions</strong> and understands how they interact. Getting assessed for ADHD by one provider and autism by another, months apart, often means neither provider sees the full picture.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          Types of professionals who can assess AuDHD:
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-text-light leading-relaxed list-disc pl-6">
          <li><strong class="text-text">Clinical psychologists</strong> with experience in adult neurodevelopmental conditions. They can diagnose but typically can't prescribe medication.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-text">Psychiatrists</strong> who specialize in ADHD and/or autism. They can both diagnose and prescribe. Harder to find, often longer wait times.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-text">Neuropsychologists</strong> who conduct comprehensive cognitive testing. Their reports tend to be the most detailed, which helps if you need formal documentation for workplace accommodations or disability support.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">What Happens During an Assessment</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Assessments vary by provider, but a thorough AuDHD evaluation usually includes several components. Expect the process to take anywhere from 2 to 6 hours, sometimes split across multiple sessions.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          A <strong class="text-text">clinical interview</strong> comes first. The assessor asks about your childhood development, school experiences, social history, sensory preferences, daily functioning, and mental health history. They're looking for lifelong patterns, not just your current experience. This is why bringing specific examples matters more than general descriptions.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          Many assessors also use <strong class="text-text">standardized questionnaires</strong>. For ADHD, common tools include the DIVA-5 or CAARS. For autism, the RAADS-R, AQ-10, or CAT-Q (which measures masking) often show up. Some providers also do cognitive testing to assess executive function, processing speed, and attention patterns directly.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          A few assessors request an <strong class="text-text">informant report</strong>, asking a parent or someone who knew you as a child to fill out a questionnaire. If your parents aren't available or didn't notice your struggles (common, especially for <a href="/learn/audhd-in-women/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">women and girls</a>), school reports, old report cards, or your own detailed childhood recollections can substitute.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">How to Prepare</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Preparation makes the difference between a productive assessment and one where you walk out feeling like they missed something. Your <a href="/learn/signs-of-audhd/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">AuDHD traits</a> might not be obvious in a clinical setting, especially if you've spent years masking. The assessor sees a calm, articulate adult. They don't see the three-hour recovery you'll need after the appointment.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          Before your assessment, write down:
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-text-light leading-relaxed list-disc pl-6">
          <li>Specific examples of how ADHD and autism show up in your daily life (not just "I have trouble focusing," but "I set 12 alarms for one appointment and still almost missed it last Tuesday")</li>
          <li>Childhood examples. Were you a picky eater? Did you line things up? Did teachers say you were smart but not trying? Were you the class daydreamer?</li>
          <li>Sensory experiences: sounds, textures, lights, or smells that bother you more than they seem to bother others</li>
          <li>Social patterns: do you mask? Do you rehearse conversations? Do you feel exhausted after socializing?</li>
          <li>Your results from any self-assessment tools (including our <a href="/quiz/is-it-audhd/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">AuDHD quiz</a>) to use as talking points</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Finding Specialists (and What to Watch For)</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Finding someone who understands AuDHD specifically is worth the extra effort. A provider who only knows ADHD might miss the autism. A provider who only knows autism might attribute your ADHD symptoms to anxiety. You need someone who sees both.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          Red flags in a provider: they dismiss self-identification entirely, they say "you can't have both," they rely heavily on eye contact and first impressions ("you don't seem autistic"), or they use outdated diagnostic criteria that don't account for masking or presentation differences in adults.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          Green flags: they ask about masking, they're familiar with how autism and ADHD interact, they ask about <a href="/learn/audhd-and-burnout/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">burnout</a>, and they take your self-report seriously rather than relying solely on observation.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          Where to search: psychology directories (Psychology Today, the ASAN provider list), neurodivergent community recommendations, and your GP for referrals. Telehealth has expanded options significantly, so you're no longer limited to your local area.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Costs and Access</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          This is the uncomfortable part. Comprehensive AuDHD assessment ranges from $500 to $3,000+ in the US without insurance coverage. In the UK, NHS wait times for adult autism assessment currently stretch to 2-5 years in many areas, pushing people toward private assessment (typically 500 to 1,500 GBP). In Australia, Medicare rebates cover part of the cost with a referral from your GP.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          If cost is a barrier, look into university psychology clinics (training clinics supervised by licensed psychologists, often at reduced rates), sliding scale providers, or organizations that specifically serve neurodivergent adults. Some people also pursue ADHD diagnosis through their GP (shorter wait, lower cost) and autism diagnosis separately, though this split approach has drawbacks mentioned above.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          Whatever route you take, the assessment itself is just information. It confirms or clarifies what you're already experiencing. If you're looking for guidance on what to do with that information, our <a href="/learn/after-your-quiz/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">after your quiz</a> page covers practical next steps.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-12 bg-accent/10 rounded-[--radius-xl] p-6 sm:p-8">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-text mb-3">Explore More</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2">
        <li><a href="/quiz/is-it-audhd/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">Take the AuDHD Quiz &rarr;</a></li>
        <li><a href="/learn/after-your-quiz/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">What to do after your quiz &rarr;</a></li>
        <li><a href="/blog/late-diagnosis-audhd/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">Late diagnosis: grief, relief, and identity &rarr;</a></li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
